UPDATE articles
SET content = '<p>Most exporters don''t actually choose between air and sea freight -- they default to whatever mode they used last time, and then justify it after the fact. That habit costs money in one direction or the other: either you''re paying an air freight premium for cargo that had three weeks of slack in the schedule, or you''re locking cash into a 30-day sea transit when a customer deadline needed speed.</p><p>The real decision isn''t "air or sea" -- it''s a trade-off between cost per kilogram and cost per day of inventory sitting in transit. Once you frame it that way, the choice usually becomes obvious.</p><h2>The Real Trade-Off: Cost Per Kilogram vs. Cost Per Day</h2><p>Air freight costs more per kilogram, often several times more than ocean freight on the same lane. Sea freight costs more in transit time -- typically three to five weeks door-to-door on major lanes out of Jebel Ali, versus one to four days by air. The question that actually matters is: what does each extra day in transit cost your business, in tied-up working capital, warehousing, or missed sales windows? For high-value, low-weight cargo, that daily cost can outweigh the freight rate difference in a single week. For bulky, low-value cargo, it rarely does.</p><div class="tech-grid"><div class="tech-card"><div class="tech-icon"><i class="fas fa-plane"></i></div><h3>Air Freight</h3><p>1-4 days transit. Higher cost per kilogram. Best for high-value, low-weight, or time-critical cargo -- electronics, pharmaceuticals, perishables, urgent restocks.</p></div><div class="tech-card"><div class="tech-icon"><i class="fas fa-ship"></i></div><h3>Sea Freight</h3><p>3-5 weeks transit on major lanes. Lower cost per kilogram, especially at volume. Best for bulky, heavy, or non-urgent cargo where inventory holding cost is manageable.</p></div></div><h2>When Air Freight Wins</h2><p>Air freight makes sense when the cargo is high-value relative to its weight, when a customer deadline or contractual penalty makes delay expensive, or when the shipment is small enough that the total air freight bill is manageable even at a premium rate. It also wins for genuinely perishable or time-sensitive goods -- pharmaceuticals with tight cold-chain windows, seasonal goods with a narrow sales period, or urgent replacement parts keeping a production line running.</p><h2>When Sea Freight Wins</h2><p>Sea freight wins on anything bulky, heavy, or where the per-unit value doesn''t justify an air premium -- furniture, construction materials, bulk consumer goods, raw materials. It also wins when your supply chain has enough lead time built in that a three-to-five-week transit doesn''t create a stockout risk. Most steady-state, planned restocking falls into this category, even for businesses that occasionally need air freight for exceptions.</p><h2>The Middle Ground: Sea-Air and Priority Ocean Services</h2><p>Between the two extremes sit hybrid options worth knowing about. Sea-air combines an ocean leg with an air leg -- typically ocean freight to a regional hub followed by an air leg for the final stretch, cutting total transit meaningfully below pure sea freight at a fraction of full air freight cost. Priority or expedited ocean services on some lanes also shave several days off standard sea transit for a moderate premium, without the cost jump of switching to air entirely. Neither is the right call for every shipment, but both are worth asking your freight forwarder about before defaulting to a straight air-or-sea decision.</p><h2>A Simple Decision Framework</h2><p>Before booking, ask three questions: What is the cargo actually worth per kilogram? What does a week of delay cost in lost sales, penalties, or tied-up capital? And is there genuine time pressure, or is this simply "the way we''ve always shipped it"? Running the numbers on cost-per-kilogram against cost-per-day-of-delay, specific to your actual cargo and deadline, turns a habitual choice into a deliberate one -- and that''s usually where the savings are found.</p>',
    excerpt = 'Most exporters default to whatever freight mode they used last time rather than actually choosing. Here''s the cost-per-kilogram versus cost-per-day framework that makes the air-versus-sea decision for you.',
    read_time = '3 min read'
WHERE id = 2;

UPDATE articles
SET content = '<p>A freight quote can look like a wall of abbreviations designed to confuse -- THC, CAF, BAF, D&D, ISPS -- and for a first-time shipper, that wall is exactly where costly assumptions creep in. Understanding what each line item actually covers, and who is contractually responsible for it, is the difference between a quote that looks cheap and a shipment that ends up expensive.</p><h2>The Basic Line Items You''ll Always See</h2><p>Every freight quote, air or sea, is built around a handful of core charges. The <strong>freight charge</strong> itself covers the actual transport -- the ocean or air leg. <strong>Terminal Handling Charges (THC)</strong> cover moving the container or cargo through the port or airport terminal, charged at both origin and destination. A <strong>documentation fee</strong> covers preparing the bill of lading or air waybill. And a <strong>customs clearance fee</strong> covers your freight forwarder or customs broker filing the import or export declaration on your behalf. These four are close to universal -- if a quote is missing one of them, ask why, because it usually means the charge is coming later, not that it doesn''t apply.</p><h2>Incoterm Determines Who Pays What</h2><p>The Incoterm on your contract -- EXW, FOB, CIF, DAP, DDP, and so on -- decides which of these charges sit on your side of the quote versus the other party''s. A quote priced under FOB terms, for example, only covers the freight from the port of loading onward; origin-side trucking and export clearance sit with the seller. The same shipment quoted DDP will bundle in duties, taxes, and final-mile delivery. Comparing two quotes without checking they''re using the same Incoterm is one of the most common ways buyers end up surprised by costs that were never actually included.</p><h2>Hidden or Variable Charges to Watch For</h2><p>Beyond the core charges, a handful of variable costs can move significantly between the quote and the final invoice. <strong>Demurrage and detention</strong> apply if your container isn''t collected or returned within the free period at the port -- these can accumulate daily and are rarely included in the initial quote since they depend on your own collection timing. A <strong>Bunker Adjustment Factor (BAF)</strong> or fuel surcharge on ocean freight, and a <strong>Currency Adjustment Factor (CAF)</strong>, both float with market conditions and are typically quoted as an estimate, not a locked figure. <strong>Storage charges</strong> at destination apply if cargo sits in a bonded warehouse waiting on clearance or collection. None of these are hidden in the sense of being deliberately concealed -- they''re standard industry charges -- but they''re easy to miss if you''re only looking at the headline freight rate.</p><h2>FCL, LCL, and Air Freight Line Items Differ</h2><p>A Full Container Load (FCL) quote is priced per container regardless of how full it is. A Less than Container Load (LCL) quote is priced per cubic metre or per tonne, whichever is greater, and usually carries proportionally higher handling fees since your cargo is being consolidated and deconsolidated with other shippers'' goods. Air freight quotes are priced on chargeable weight -- the greater of actual weight or volumetric weight -- which catches out shippers moving bulky, lightweight cargo who expect to be billed on actual kilograms alone.</p><h2>Red Flags in a Quote</h2><p>A quote that is dramatically cheaper than competing quotes on the same lane and same Incoterm is worth a direct question before booking, not after. Common causes are a missing charge that will appear later, an Incoterm mismatch that shifts cost onto you at a different stage, or an unrealistic transit time that doesn''t account for current port congestion or vessel schedules. A reputable freight forwarder will walk through every line item on request -- reluctance to do that is itself a signal.</p><h2>A Simple Checklist Before You Sign</h2><p>Confirm the Incoterm and what it includes on each side. Ask whether THC, documentation, and customs clearance are included at both origin and destination. Check whether BAF, CAF, or fuel surcharges are locked or estimated. Ask about free time at the destination port before demurrage applies. And compare quotes only when they''re quoting the same Incoterm, the same transit assumptions, and the same scope of service -- otherwise you''re not actually comparing like for like.</p>',
    excerpt = 'THC, CAF, BAF, D&D -- a freight quote can read like a wall of abbreviations. Here''s what each line item actually covers, who''s responsible under your Incoterm, and the variable charges that catch first-time shippers out.',
    read_time = '4 min read'
WHERE id = 14;
